The math shown towards the end of the video has a slight mistake in the ordering of the state variables. It should look like this:
<div class="mathquill">
\begin{bmatrix}
z\\ 
\psi\\ 
\dot{z}\\ 
\dot{\psi}
\end{bmatrix}'

= 

\begin{bmatrix}
z\\ 
\psi\\ 
\dot{z}\\ 
\dot{\psi}
\end{bmatrix}

+

dt 

\begin{bmatrix}
\dot{z}\\ 
\dot{\psi}\\ 
\ddot{z}\\ 
\ddot{\psi}
\end{bmatrix}
</div>

If we wanted to figure out the size of the moment about the x axis, <span class="mathquill">M_x</span>, caused by the **right-most propeller**, we'd do the following:

<div class="mathquill">
\begin{aligned}
M_x &= F \times d_{\text{perp,x}}
\\
M_x &= F \times L
\end{aligned}
</div>

Here, the perpendicular distance to the x axis, <span class="mathquill">d_{\text{perp,x}}</span>, is exactly equal to the length of the propeller arm. 

